@NODE "APatch" "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"
@{b}Introduction:@{ub}

À What is it and what it does

    APatch is a small patch that replaces some OS' functions with faster and 020+ optimized ones. Although you may not notice any difference... Due to fact that some of the system IO routines are patched to execute faster one can't measure their speed properly without hiting the hardware directly... 

À What patches are replaced?

    À ExecPatch 
    À CPUClr
    À CopyMemQuicker
    À FastWaitBlit
    À IPatch, FastInterrupts
    À FasterForbid
    À BlackBorder
    and probably more (sooner or later)

À How it works

    Apatch was made in a such way that it allocates a few hundred bytes, patches functions to point to that allocated area then quits.

À Why?

Because it's a speedup patch not another patch that would waste the precious CPU time.    

À Is it possible to remove it safely?

Currently, you cannot neither deactivate them nor remove them... (it won't survive reset of course)


@{b}Patched exec.library functions:@{ub}

    À ExitIntr() - AP
    À Schedule() - AP
    À Reschedule() - 
    À Switch() - AP
    À Dispatch() - AP
    À Exception() - AP
    À Forbid() - 
    À Permit() - AH
    À Cause() - AP
    À Insert() - 
    À AddHead() - 
    À AddTail() - 
    À Remove() - AH
    À Enqueue() - AH
    À SetSignal()
    À SetExcept()
    À Wait()
    À Signal() - AP
    À GetMsg() - AP
    À ReplyMsg() - AP
    À RemPort() - 
    À WaitPort() - AP
    À DoIO() - AP
    À CheckIO() - AH
    À WaitIO() - AP
    À ObtainSemaphore() - AH
    À CopyMem() - AH & AP 
    À CopyMemQuick() - AH


@{b}Patched graphics.library functions:@{ub}

    À WaitBlit() - AP
    À Draw() - AP 
    À BltClear() - MN
    À LockLayerRom() - AP 
    À UnlockLayerRom() - AP

@{b}CPU Interrupt Vectors patched:@{ub}

    À Level 1 Autovector
    À Level 2 Autovector
    À Level 3 Autovector
    À Level 4 Autovector
    À Level 5 Autovector
    À Level 6 Autovector

Interrupt routines are based on Dave Jones' idea, but it took a while to implement it properly...    

AP - Adam Polkosnik
AH - Arthur Hagen
DJ - Dave Jones
MN - Mattias Nilsson

and there is more to come... :-)

Apatch was written 100% in asm pc-relative code (whatever this means... anyway all optimisations were swithed off during the assembling;-) )  

@{b}Note to antivirus guys:@{ub}
You can recognize my patches by 'DC1!' at offset -$c from the start of a patch. 
I.E.

    dc.l $44,$43,$31,$21 ; "DC1!"  
    dc.l xxxxxxxx ; status flags 
    dc.l xxxxxxxx ; pointer to previous function
MyNewFunction:
    moveq #0,d0
    ...
(If you have any good idea about doing it in a better way please DO contact me!!! PLEASE!!!)

@{b}Note to patch writers:@{ub}

I'm open for any ideas...
Ask me if you want the source code...
